âœ… REACT NOTES (Corrected + Expanded Version)
1) Data Binding in React
âœ… Definition

Data Binding means connecting data (JS values/state/props) with UI elements so that UI displays the data properly.

âœ… React Data Binding Syntax

In JSX, React binds data using:

{ }


ðŸ“Œ Because: JSX is like HTML + JavaScript, so React uses { } to embed JS expressions inside HTML-like code.

////////////////////////////////////////////////


2) Data for Component using State
âœ… Definition

State is a memory of a component used to store dynamic/changing data.

âœ… Example dynamic values:

user input

API response

count

product stock status

ðŸ“Œ Because: If data changes after rendering, React needs state to trigger UI re-render.


/////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////



3) useState() Hook
âœ… Definition

useState() is a React Hook used to:
âœ… Create state variable and âœ… change it using setter function

âœ… Syntax
const [state, setState] = useState(initialValue);


Example:

const [count, setCount] = useState(0);


ðŸ“Œ Because: React UI updates only when state changes via setter function.


//////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////



âœ… FAQ (Sir Style)


âœ… FAQ 1: When to set state?

âœ… Answer:
State can be configured with new values:

on Mount phase

on any specific Event

âŒ You canâ€™t set values into state while creating the component.

ðŸ“Œ Because: Component creation phase runs before UI is ready. State updates should happen after component is mounted or by events.

âœ… FAQ 2: How to configure the Mount phase for component?

âœ… Answer:
Mount and Unmount phases are handled by using useEffect() hook.

4) useEffect() Hook
âœ… Definition

useEffect() is used to perform side effects in React like:

fetching data

setting values on mount

updating title

subscriptions/timers

cleanup on unmount

âœ… Syntax (Sir format)
useEffect(() => {
  // actions on mount
}, [dependencies]);

âœ… Notes

Every component mounts on the first request

If you want a component to mount / re-run again:
âœ… define dependencies

ðŸ“Œ Because: React runs the effect again when any dependency value changes.

âœ… Binding Various Data Types in React
1) Number Type
âœ… Definition

A number in JavaScript can be:

signed integer: -10

unsigned integer: 10

float: 3.4

double: 23.33

decimal: 235.8321

exponent: 2e3

hexadecimal: 0x9001

binary: 0b1010

octal: 0o456

bigint: 9838286462n

ðŸ“Œ Because: JavaScript uses a flexible number system, so React can display all these formats.

âœ… Formatting Numbers

Numbers are presented using methods:

a) toFixed()

Fix decimal places.

(12.345).toFixed(2); // "12.35"

b) toPrecision()

Keeps total significant digits.

(123.456).toPrecision(4); // "123.5"

c) toLocaleString()

Formats number based on locale.

âœ… Example currency:

const [price] = useState(500000);

<p>
  {price.toLocaleString("en-IN", { style: "currency", currency: "INR" })}
</p>


âœ… Extra knowledge:

style: "currency" | "decimal" | "percent" | "unit"

notation: "compact" | "scientific"

ðŸ“Œ Because: Users understand formatted values better (ex: â‚¹5,00,000 instead of 500000).

âœ… Number Parsing (same as JS)

parseInt()

parseFloat()

ðŸ“Œ Because: user inputs usually come as strings.

âœ… Checking a Number

Use:

isNaN(value)


âœ… returns true if value is NOT a number

Example:

isNaN("abc") // true
isNaN("10")  // false

2) Boolean Type
âœ… Definition

Boolean values are configured using:

true

false

âœ… Important Notes (Sir points)

React canâ€™t display boolean directly in UI, it can only use it in conditions.

React canâ€™t treat boolean as number 0 & 1
(like old JS logic: 0=false, 1=true)

JSX canâ€™t use statements
âœ… only expressions

ðŸ“Œ Because: JSX expects expressions that return a value, not full JS blocks like if, for.

âœ… Syntax
const [stock] = useState(true);

<p>
  {(stock === true) ? "True" : "False"}
</p>


âœ… Better short version:

<p>{stock ? "In Stock" : "Out of Stock"}</p>

3) String Type
âœ… Definition

React supports all JS string formats:

Single quote ' '

Double quote " "

Backtick `

âœ… Special Point

Backtick allows binding expressions using:

${ }


So:

${ } â†’ JavaScript Data Binding

{ } â†’ React Data Binding

ðŸ“Œ Because: backticks create template literals which allow inserting expressions.

âœ… Example
const [styleClass] = useState("bg-danger text-white");

<p className={`border border-2 p-2 border-warning ${styleClass}`}>
  Hello
</p>


âœ… Using concatenation:

<p className={"border border-2 p-2 border-warning " + styleClass}>
  Hello
</p>

âœ… String methods/properties (same as JS)

length

startsWith()

endsWith()

charAt()

charCodeAt()

includes()

indexOf()

lastIndexOf()

match()

slice()

split()

trim()

toUpperCase()

toLowerCase() etc.

4) Null & Undefined
âœ… Definition

null and undefined are same as JavaScript.

undefined â†’ value is not assigned

null â†’ value is assigned intentionally as empty

ðŸ“Œ Because: In forms, prompt() can return null when cancel is pressed.

âœ… Example
const [name, setName] = useState();

setName(prompt("Enter Name")); // string | null

<p>
  {(name === null) ? "Name is required" : name}
</p>


âœ… Best improvement:

{name ? name : "Name is required"}

5) Symbol
âœ… Definition

Symbol is a JavaScript primitive type.

âœ… It is used to create unique hidden fields inside objects.

ðŸ“Œ Because: Symbol properties wonâ€™t be easily accessed in loops, so they help in encapsulation.

âœ… Example (Corrected formatting)
<script>
  var id = Symbol();
  var product = {
    [id]: 1,
    name: "TV",
    price: 45000
  };

  for (var property in product) {
    document.write(property + "<br>");
  }

  document.write(product[id]);
</script>


âœ… Output:

for loop prints: name, price

symbol field doesnâ€™t print

but can be accessed using: product[id]

âœ… Summary (Quick Revision)

{ } â†’ React data binding

${ } â†’ JavaScript string template binding

useState() â†’ create + update state

useEffect() â†’ mount/unmount + side effects

booleans canâ€™t display directly (must use condition)

toLocaleString() best for currency display in React
